rdiac suction","Gravitational force"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkeletal muscle contraction\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism driving venous return from the lower limbs. When skeletal muscles contract, they compress the veins, forcing blood upward against gravity. This is known as the skeletal muscle pump or peripheral venous pump. One-way venous valves prevent retrograde flow, ensuring blood moves only towards the heart.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArterial pressure gradient\u003C/strong\u003E - While arterial pressure provides initial forward flow, it is largely dissipated by the time blood reaches the venous system\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac suction\u003C/strong\u003E - The heart\u0027s ability to create negative pressure during diastole has minimal effect on peripheral venous return\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous smooth muscle contraction\u003C/strong\u003E - Veins have relatively little smooth muscle and their contraction plays a minor role in blood flow\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGravitational force\u003C/strong\u003E - Gravity actually opposes venous return in the upright position\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther factors that assist venous return include respiratory pump action (negative intrathoracic pressure during inspiration) and the presence of venous valves that prevent retrograde flow.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Venous blood flow is primarily driven by skeletal muscle contraction and respiratory movements rather than cardiac activity.","Venous valves prevent retrograde flow and help maintain forward movement of blood against gravity.","The negative intrathoracic pressure during inspiration aids venous return to the right atrium."],"references":["Tortora GJ, 